weather %>% ggplot(aes(x=LONGITUDE,y=LATITUDE)) + geom_point(aes(colour=ELEVATION),size=1) + scale_color_gradient(low="turquoise2", high="gold1")

Add state information and time zone using the maps package.

states_map <- map_data("state")
weather %>% group_by(STATE) %>% summarise(state=unique(STATE),long=mean(LONGITUDE),lat=mean(LATITUDE)) -> state_summ
weather %>% select(LONGITUDE,LATITUDE,STATE,`UTC OFFSET`) %>% mutate(STATE=abbr2state(STATE)) -> state_utc
colnames(state_utc) <- c("long","lat","region","time_zone")


ggplot()+ geom_map(data = state_utc, map=states_map, aes(fill=factor(time_zone), map_id = tolower(region))) + geom_map(data = states_map, map = states_map, aes(map_id=region),color="white", fill=NA, size=0.5) + geom_point(mapping = aes(LONGITUDE,LATITUDE,colour=ELEVATION),data=weather,size=1) + scale_color_gradient(low="turquoise2", high="gold1")+theme_classic() + geom_text(mapping = aes(long,lat, label=state),data = state_summ) + geom_label() + labs(fill="UTC OFFSET")

Here is an alternative, but very similar method:

myurl <- "ftp://ftp.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/data/ushcn/v2.5/ushcn.tavg.latest.raw.tar.gz"
mytmp <- tempfile()
download.file(myurl, mytmp)

untar(mytmp)
files <- as_tibble(list.files("ushcn.v2.5.5.20190204"))
